TY  - JOUR
T1  - Turnover Theory at the Empirical Interface: Problems of Fit and Function
AU  - Steel, Robert P.
Y1  - 2002/07/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2002.7389900
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2002.7389900
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 346
EP  - 360
VL  - 27
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - There are problems of fit between standard research practices in the domain of turnover research and evolutionary decisional processes like job search. I analyze this problem from methodological, empirical, and conceptual vantage points. Reanalysis of data suggests that the ability to accurately estimate employment opportunity is related to one's temporal positioning within the turnover process. Using cybernetic decision theory as a point of departure, I propose a model conceptualizing employment search processes as a series of decision stages.
AB  - There are problems of fit between standard research practices in the domain of turnover research and evolutionary decisional processes like job search. I analyze this problem from methodological, empirical, and conceptual vantage points. Reanalysis of data suggests that the ability to accurately estimate employment opportunity is related to one's temporal positioning within the turnover process. Using cybernetic decision theory as a point of departure, I propose a model conceptualizing employment search processes as a series of decision stages.
